description.text:
This is a mounting system for the RealAcc x210 V+ quad frame and the FRSKY XM+ receiver. There are two holes in the top of the frame that seem perfect for running the two receiver antennas through, but it could use a bit of protection. This fits over these antenna holes and allows you to use ordinary coffee stir sticks as cheap antenna protectors. This keeps the antennas at a 45-degree angle for best reception. The rear portion provides some protection for my VTX antenna so that in a crash the antenna does not impact the props.

This mounts securely to the frame using the zip tie holes at the top rear of the frame

This piece is rather specific to my setup, but I am sharing it here in the hopes that others may find it helpful.

title: Speed loaders for SIG and Ruger
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Speed loaders for:
SIG P227 45
SIG P227 9mm
SIG SP2022 9mm
SIG Mosquito 22
Ruger LCP 380
Ruger LC9 9mm Be safe.

These are speed loaders designed specifically for some SIG and Ruger handguns. The manufacturer, model and caliber are shown in the file name. This design is sort of a knock-off of the design by jsteuben. I tried different "improvements" to his design but none of the improvements made it work much better except for tighter tolerances on the design. I beefed up some parts. These are designed for a specific magazine and other similar caliber magazines from other gun manufacturers may not work. If you use one of these speed loaders, be safe! Also, the speed loader does not put a bullet in the magazine. You do. It's just a tool to save your fingers and thumb when loading magazines. Operating instructions: Put your magazine in the speed loader. If you have a solid surface to work on, it's easier if you rest the bottom of the magazine on the work surface. Push the speed loader down and it will clear a path for the next bullet. You'll only be able to shove the bullet half way in. Then pull up the speed loader and push the bullet the rest of the way into the magazine. It really saves wear and tear on the fingers. I don't think it's faster than loading by hand, just easier. There are some commercial speed loaders in Amazon and other stores. They have some advantages over this design. If your semiautomatic handgun is not listed, follow these instructions to get one that will work (no guarantees):
1) pick the same caliber if possible; if not, pick a smaller one (if you have a 22, pick the file 22_SIG_speed_loader_ver8.stl, not the other one for the Mosquito)
2) flip the part on the build plate and print the bottom 1/4" of the speed loader.
3) check and see if your magazine will go through the small piece you just printed.
4) if it does, print the speed loader. There's a 95% chance it will work for you.
5) if the speed loader is too small, scale it up and redo steps 2 & 3. I would expect the scaling to be very small, maybe 101% to 104%. Parts list: None. Assembly instructions: None. Printing instructions: Adhesion to the build plate is very important. All of the speed loaders were printed on a Makerbor Replicator2
  • PLA (Makerbot filament)
  • Printed: Low(faster) resolution, 8% infill, 2 shells, 0.30 mm layer height, 230C

title: Orange Pi Zero Ultra Compact Case

description.text:
I designed from scratch this case because I wanted a case o most compact possible (to save filament when printing and to carry easily).
After 3 iterations, and a lot of measures with a digital caliper I design the smallest case on the Thingiverse.

MAIN FEATURES

  • Very compact (its the smallest case possible only 49x52x34 mm)
  • Well vented from all the sides
  • Antenna position interchangeable (but you can also choose to keep the antenna inside the case)
  • LEDs windows
  • Squared box that can be used in different orientations
  • Reinforced mount poles (with ribs when possible)

What do you need:

  • 2 small M3 screws (M3x5 - button head)
  • 4 M3 bolts (flat head with at least 8mm, I used this excellent black bolts from Aliexpress M3x12)
  • M3 tap (highly recommended to open threads)

When you should choose another case

  • You don't have a properly calibrated printer that cannot print with precision small holes and 1.2 mm walls (This is a complicated object to be printed)
  • You don't like tight fits. The placement of the objects is critical, and you have a little margin to play
  • You need a small fan or a big heatsink (I used a small aluminum heatsink and because I will not perform very CPU intensive tasks I don't need to worry a lot about cooling)
  • You need a stronger/robust case (I used 1,2 mm walls so it's not the toughest cases)
  • You don't have the Orange Pi extension board
  • You need to use the GPIOs pins or the serial monitor pins
  • You need a big IR window for the side sensor

This is a followup to:

http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2598673
without further adieu....

Attack 3: KOOPLA THE LACK

Next thing was to find a good way to mount a power bar on the Lack...
Ever since I picked up a couple of koopla power bars with built in usb power (for my octopi) I knew i'd put it on the stack...
I noticed first that the power bar appeared to be built to mount in a track (a lack track?) but searched for anything at Ikea that it clipped into without luck.
Apparently, its built to slid/snap into a SIGNUM shelf mount which apparently like the deeper cabinets isn't available in Canada... (Come on Ikea! What gives? give us the good bits lol...).

Searching Thingiverse I found lots of Koppla mounts, but they all hooked the ends, nothing used the built in track mount, so I modeled the powerbar, then got to work...
I initially thought of building it based on the lack stack adapter and sliding it onto a leg, but then opted to go with a 3m tape based mount which would stick to the underside of the printer level. I opted to include screw holes but haven't used them, I'll save that for when I decide the best place to mount it.
I also went back and finished the initial design to slide up a leg and mount that way, although I haven't printed it I'm 99% sure it'll be just fine, if you go that route please let me know how it turns out, if there are issues I'll adjust it asap.

As always, comments are greatly appreciated, in this case direction and pitfalls to watch for are also appreciated, If you've been here done this and have a better way please let me know.

-Changed the origin to import in the correct print orientation, for novice users
-Made the initial slope at the base even more gradual, to make printing easier across more printer types.
-Doubled the polygons on the print for a more continuous circular object.

title: Alto saxophone mouthpiece and unique lig system

description.text: I designed this mouthpiece to give me a nice edgy sound, punchy but still mellow enough for a jazz big-band. It about a 1.7mm tip opening, average lay length. I designed the rather novel reed clamping system as well, which allows rapid reed change mid-concert!

I've made a couple of iterations on this project, and had the mouthpiece itself laser-sintered in stainless steel. It now plays REALLY well, and have used it in several jazz concerts. Surprisingly, the ABS plastic version printed on the Makerbot sounds as good as the stainless steel sintered one. This one was printed at 50% fill and using raft and break-away support. Not sure how durable it is at this density, might try one at 100% fill. There is a fair bit of cleaning up to do on the reed table. Ideally, you'll need some fine sandpaper on a piece of flat glass and then holding the piece flat against it, gradually polish the reed table of the piece until all the raft marks disappear. Then, gradually work the facing out to the tip, making sure to finish it off with about 1.6 to 1.8mm tip opening. Persevere, after about 20 minutes this one played like a dream, from bottom Bb right up to altissimo C! Recording is included below. I'm obviously not playing soprano and alto at the same time, its an overdub;-) You'll need to cut a small square of 1.5mm rubber to go in the ligature clamp. The lever then drives over-centre and provides the clamping action. I think its a really neat idea, and lets you change a reed very quickly. I probably should have patented this, but there you go you've all got it for free! I'm also working on the soprano and tenor versions..... (end July hopefully). If anyone makes this piece, gets it to play and likes it, I'd love to hear from you (email below). Thanks, have fun! [email protected] Revisions: A2 - bore opened 0.5mm, was too tight on cork. Reinforcement added to avoid plastic version splitting when fitting to cork. Table added to give stability to ligature and retain it. Rubber insert can now be deleted.

title: Invisible Thread Reel
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Here is my version of a "Invisible Thread Reel".
Most magician will know what is it good for.

I try to work with very thin kevlar threads. But in the standard tube-like reels the ultra thin tread breaks very often. Changing the thread takes me more then 20min. Each time...
So pure time wasting!

In a video with John Finn he showed his old self-made reel. It was contained in a pillbox.

Based on that design I tried different housing-sizes, reel-diameter, rubber-band-length and so on.

This is now my 5th design. Features:

  • Pull out length of 2m is possible. (may be more?)
  • Very quite (if not pulled out to fast)
  • Very easy to add a new wax ball to the left over thread
  • Very easy to set pre-tension, by turning the rubber loops on the angers
  • Very easy and quick replacing the hole spinner
  • Size is okay to stay in my jeans front pocket or be attached in a Jacket.
  • ... and - of course - easy to print.

I bought the rubber band in a hand-craft store. It is provided for stretchable bracelets.
I recommend to attach one piece of rubber band on each spinner half before glueing them together.

All of modules are screwed using machine m3 (mainly 10mm) bolts.

The x-tensioner also fits standard MK8 extruder setup from ANET A8.

Next step is to add connector to make electronics modular but I still have some thinking to do before publishing anything.

title: Anet A8 electronics box with MOSFETs and PI
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
While I found several electronics cases for the A8, I wanted one that included 2 MOSFETs as well as a Raspberry PI, while still matching the frame design. So I decided to design one myself. While it's not a remix of any one of the already existing designs, most of those showed me how I wanted the design to be - or not... So thanks to all those who gave me some inspiration.
This case is designed to give room for the A8 stock mainboard and 2 MOSFETs for running hotbed and extruder without melting the mainboard... In addition, it's deep enough so you can put in a raspberry pi as print and camera server on top of the mainboard using a separate frame.
The case uses the original mounting holes for the mainboard, the screws will go through the pi frame, the mainboard and the case. The PI is supposed to be mounted to the underside of the frame and put on top of the mainboard in missionary posiition.
The opening for the interfaces is kept in a generic form also known as big rectangle ;) so you could put in some other board on top of the mainboard by just using a different frame for mounting it. The cover has an opening to mount a 90mm fan to get enough cooling to the mainboard when it's sandwiched with a PI. If you don't want a fan, you might just put some grid in the place.
As this is my first attempt at 3D-design, it certainly leaves much to be improved, especially the frame carrying the PI is quite fragile and needs some improvement. I haven't actually printed this version, I made some changes to the wiring openings after the experiences with a first prototype.I'll probably switch to a metal frame soon anyway, so I probably will not do further work on this.

Edit: I've added the fcstd file for easier remixing. As this was my first attempt at 3-D-design and wasn't meant for public use, it might not be quite up to current documentation and design quality standards. Also there might be some Umlauts lurking in there. In plain english: enter at your own risk ;)

Like on my two other exoskeletons, this mod uses a 6mm carbon fiber tube (it can be replaced by a steel or aluminium rod).
The rod is hold in position when tightening the mounting screws.

description.text:
I have a colleague into bee-keeping and he wanted me to print the original remix, after printing it he decided to use it for the rest of his hives and I wanted to do a better job with the requirements.

Everything is in OpenSCAD and written to be parametric.
I am still testing it out, consider this version as RC1 or Beta if you prefer.

It is design to be 2 parts as I am using 300x300 build plate. If you cannot fit it on your printer - OpenSCAD does make it easy. Version might be incoming.

If you are using CNC = I would be interested in a remix or feedback for wood cutting.

Creality CR-10

mm

Notes:

Infill should barely matter as the pieces are thin - feel free to experiment.
Beware of warping even with PLA - lower speed, lower temperature if you get warped edges.

Generic White PLA

Sanding

Sand landing a bit so it glues nicely.
Sand away all pesky artifacts

Gluing

The idea is to glue landing and brackets together.
This should be done on site as your dimensions might differ.

Gluing the plates together is a question of using some design over it as a handle.
I have used prototypes or models from other builds, no need to design a new thing - you will have plenty of things laying around.

Used both existing models as inspiration

OpenSCAD is easy once you understand the idea behind the build.

1) Small holes are for closed hive
2) Larger holes are for open hive during colder months when other animals might want to crawl in
3) it has to be removable as you do not want it on during busy season
4) Landing is requires for bees to properly land and not crawl around the holes.

Known issues
  • Printing is more difficult to the grid having sharp edges (Fixed by introducing intersection)
  • Small holes in the bridges caused by incorrect nozzle width (Slicer settings)
  • No supports for the landing - should be included in the model (Slicer settings)
  • No grid on first layer.

I printed it with rafts and supports as a test run, but I would not recommend it in general, the insets make cleaning the model up a mess.

This was designed in Rhino. Having a radially extruded text component is not trivial and I cannot do that with any other software.

The process is as follows:

  1. Create two cylinders, corresponding to the internal and external face of the text (there will be a third cylinder afterwards, the inner wall of the ring.
  2. Open the cylinders up by splitting them on one side using a line or a plane.
  3. Unroll the cylinders to get a rectangle that exactly represents the cylinder side, attached to each cylinder's walls.
  4. Render your text as curves. Make two copies, one corresponding to the front cylinder, one to the back cylinder.
  5. Scale 1-d the text on the back cylinder down, using the ratio between the two unrolled cylinder width's as ratio. This is because the inner circle is smaller, the text is actually shrunk down along the text direction.
  6. Use the Bend command to wrap the text around the cylinders.
  7. You need to realize the letters' wall. For this purpose, first use a Pull command from the curves to the respective cylinders, to make sure the curve has the right degree to adhere to the cylinders.
  8. Use Sweep2 (sweep two rails) to make all the letters' walls. Create some cross section curves to help if needed -- all the curves that make the letters up have at least one end or a mid point that can be used to correctly map one to the other.
  9. Create the back face of the letters by trimming the inner cylinder at the inner text.
  10. Create the profile of the actual napkin ring, as you please, e.g. as a closed curved line.
  11. Revolve it around the text.
  12. Trim off the text side walls excess from the front, and trim the revolved surface inside the letter's area.
  13. Join as a unique polysurface.

Optionally, you could do 10 and 11 before 7 and pull the external curve directly onto the napkin ring.

description.text:
I noticed that my bottles did not fit in the fastrack12 even though the homebrew store specifically says that they do fit. I found out that they fit if the bottle cap was removed, but that would defeat the whole prupose of storing my mead in these. I did the only logical thing and designed an adapter of course!

This should work with the patent corks still on the bottle.

Other notes:
The model is made to be 16cm tall, which lets roughly 1/4 of it sit inside the fastrack and create stable footing. Despite this I tried shrinking it to 15cm tall and had the metal bars from the patent cork catch the walls of the adapter. I tried putting pressure on it by hand, but it did not break. I stood up and put my upper body into it and it cracked. I did it again and it finally broke.

Needless to say that when you print this at the right size and the pressure gets split all around the top of the adapter, it will be no problem. I probably put 10kg or more pressure on it with only 2 places to absorb the weight, while a normal sized adapter will be able to dsitribute the weight throughout itself.

title: Infrared LED Mount for Prusa I3 MK2S

description.text:
This is a mount for the little IR Illuminator modules you can buy from amazon/ebay/china etc. It's designed to clamp onto the frame of the Prusa I3 Mk2S, It may or may not fit other printers - feel free to remix it so it does!

I've cut a hole out to allow the heatsink free air - Not sure if it gets hot enough to deform PLA yet, so you might want to print in something a bit more heat resistant...

Work in progress!

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

i3 MK2S

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.15mm

Infill:

Cubic 15%

Post-processing will mostly consist of sanding any tight areas for clearance - the board may or may not fit into the mount cleanly without easing the sides a little, and the mount & bracket may need some reworking.

I printed with Prusa's Optimal 0.15mm layer height in silver PLA, which seemed pretty close initially, but I had to go in and add ease the joints a little in the model, depending on the material used and your printer, the tolerances may still be too tight.

I knocked this up over a day or so using Onshape, I started off with measurements of the module and started with the footprint, building up the sides, adding the cut-out for the heatsink, adding the extrusions & holes for the wires, then finally built up the bracket, mount and pin.

I've added some clearance around the mount and bracket interface, depending on the material printed and the accuracy of your printer, you may want need to do some sanding to make the joint work properly.

The pin was a bit of an afterthought, and probably isn't worth bothering with, but if you want to try it, go nuts - M3 screw and nut seems to do the trick.

The Onshape files are public and available here

title: Parametric Rocket Fin Alignment Guide / Jig
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Update 7/2: v2.0 - Now with sleeve option for attaching fins on different places along the tube.
I wanted to make it easy to attach just about any number of fins on just about any size rocket tube, and so I came up with this fully parametric model. You can even print one that supports different numbers of fins at the same time (e.g. 3 and 4 -- see photo). 
It's smart about fin alignment, too, providing internal support where the fin is attached, and offsetting the guide block to compensate for the thickness of the fin material itself. 
I printed a rather small one here so we could fasten three cardboard fins onto a paper towel tube, but it's very easy to configure it for something different. For example, you can print one to attach five fins to a thick shipping tube -- just tweak the parameters a bit. I've annotated one of the images so you can see many (not all) the parameters that are available, or you can just look at the comments in the OpenSCAD code. There's even a standoff setting to help prevent gluing the jig to the rocket. 
It's also smart about filament -- there's not a lot wasted here. The one in the photos required about a meter of 3mm filament, costing about US$0.25.
The STL is useful for gluing fins cut out of beverage container cardboard on to a paper towel tube (as you'll see in the pictures), but you'll probably want to configure it to suit your own specific building materials. 
Available parameters define the size of the rocket body (inside and outside diameter of the tube); the number of fins; the fin thickness, height, length elevation, and standoff (from body); the thickness of the fin support material and spine length (for stability); the thickness of the support material for the tube, and the thickness of the base.

1) Change the values in "User-defined values" to suit your needs. If you want it to support both 3- and 4-fin configurations, use an array like [3,4] for finQty. 
2) Print and clean up if necessary. 
3) Insert tube, and clip fins to the guides. You can add glue before you attach them, but be sure you have set the standoff value so you don't accidentally glue the jig to the rocket. I just glue one side first with a bead of hot glue, and then remove the jog to glue the other side.

title: Creality CR-10S Z axis stop extender

description.text:
This little yet cleverly designed piece, slips in the lower edge of the left vertical carriage to make it meet the end stop switch to bring a few millimeters extra of clearance.

This solves the problem some CR-10S and upgraded CR-10 have: when the Z axe slides the X beam downwards, the right carriage lower edge ends up resting against the second motor support just a tad before the left carriage lower edge triggers the Z end switch, thus slightly tilting the X beam, such that it loses its horizon in part of its Z axis trajectory. This tiny piece triggers the switch at an higher height, preventing the unwanted contact in the right side.

To install, slide the notch under the carriage plate, right above the switch. Notice the shape, trimmed to prevent the contact against the vertical post, and ensure the matching of this trimming. You may need to add some blue tape inside the notch to make it fit more tightly.

Edition: You may need to add some washers under the bed's springs to keep the tension needed to level it. [Thanks to Cymen to remind me of this detail in the comments].

title: Nova Soft Jaws
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I got the idea for this project from Rakuron's work in progress.

It didn't make sense to have to print the whole jaw set with 100% infill only to cut away what you didn't need on the lathe. I have included the Fusion 360 file so that you can modify the model to make jaws sized for your specific needs. This method will allow you to print the jaw set with less infill and save on filament.

I took a lot of test prints, but I was able to successfully add the curved alignment guide on the back of each jaw. Between this guide and the chamfered screw holes, the jaws mount perfectly everytime!

I've included only one STL file. Printing a set of four of these will hold a cylinder between 2.1" and 2.7" in diameter on your Nova chuck. Or, at least that's what I get on my SuperNova2 chuck.

https://youtu.be/szPDt2CxGxo

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2 Layer Height

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Supports are needed to print this STL file. I would recommend printing such that the surface that mates to the chuck is the topmost layer. Although this will require more filament for the support structure, it will be easy to clean off using your lathe and chuck!

Wall Thickness is very important for a strong structure. The natural PETG jaws I printed have a 2.0 mm Wall Thickness.

I'm sure ABS would be a fine material as well. If you wanted to try a flexible, like TPU, be sure to increase your infill and maybe the Wall Thickness.

comments.text: Honestly, I was hoping to inspire someone else more skilled at 3d modeling than I to improve upon my design. So thank you very much! :D

title: Yet Another CR-10 E3D v6 mount

description.text:
I had previously printed out "CR-10 50 x 15 Double Blower Fan Fang Mount
by dhien2" (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2481055) for the stock hot end on my CR-10, but recently purchased an e3d clone. I wanted to keep the ability to easily switch from one to the other if I had the need, but didn't see any options that I really liked so I decided to create an e3d v6 mount that would fit the dual fan fang mount that I had already printed :)

After finding a few e3d mounts here on thingiverse that had source files available, opened them up and got the measurements I needed. I then proceeded to build a mount with the appropriate measurements that would fit and work with the fan mount I already had. And this is the result :D

I have included .stl's for both the front and back separately, as well as one where they are both in one file. I have also included my fusion 360 .f3d file if anyone wants to do any tweaking to the file in case one of the measurements I used wasn't exactly right.

I hope somebody finds it useful.

Printer:

CR-10

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

15

Notes:

I would believe supports are needed on the back section for the recessed area and post holes from the bed, and the two slots for retaining nuts, but that is ultimately up to you, the user :). The front section should be fine.

This print requires 2x m3x8 screws to attach the mount to the carriage, 2x m3x16 & 2x m3 nuts to attach the front mount to the rear mount
